<div id="review_108165231" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/108165231" />
    <a title="Patti" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3197487-patti"><img alt="Patti" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1275236342p2/3197487.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/108165231?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Patti" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Patti" href="/user/show/3197487-patti">Patti</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer108165231&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer108165231" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16692354483276012524">The premise of this book is very interesting--the main character (Harper) was struck by lightning as a teenager. She survived and found she had a new ability--she can hear dead people &quot;calling&quot; to her. With help from her stepbrother, Tolliver, she turns this ability into a business.<br/><br/>I liked the premise and I liked the brief glimpses given into Harper&apos;s (and Tolliver&apos;s) upbringing...Harper&apos;s mom and dad were lawyers and quite affluent until they got caught up with the people they represented (as H</span>
  <span id="freeText16692354483276012524" style="display:none">The premise of this book is very interesting--the main character (Harper) was struck by lightning as a teenager. She survived and found she had a new ability--she can hear dead people "calling" to her. With help from her stepbrother, Tolliver, she turns this ability into a business.<br /><br />I liked the premise and I liked the brief glimpses given into Harper's (and Tolliver's) upbringing...Harper's mom and dad were lawyers and quite affluent until they got caught up with the people they represented (as Harper says). Tolliver's dad and Harper's mom got married at some point, and the downward spiral continued. <br /><br />The thing that I didn't like was the relationship between Tolliver and Harper. It was creepy, to put it mildly. Some parts literally made my skin crawl. The attraction between the two of them was so obvious that I had to question why the author made them "related" in the first place. SPOILER SPOILER SPOILER SCROLL DOWN<br /><br /><br />It was obvious that the two were going to end up screwing, and they did. The book started out with them calling each other brother and sister and ended with them banging each other and declaring undying love. Soooo...why did the author even go this route? Why not make them old family friends or something? I found their whole relationship pre-boink to be just gross. Post-boink, I was okay with it. <br /><br />I just checked out the first two books in the series so I can see the genesis of the relationship. Maybe they were less gross in the first two installments? So long as I can ignore the relationship between the two, I really enjoy the books!</span>
  <a data-text-id="16692354483276012524" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


